{"doc":{"isMarkdown":true,"isTranslated":false,"isActive":true,"flaws":{},"title":"Server-sent events","mdn_url":"/en-US/docs/Web/API/Server-sent_events","locale":"en-US","native":"English (US)","sidebarHTML":"<ol><li><strong><a href=\"/en-US/docs/Web/API/Server-sent_events\">Server-sent events</a></strong></li><li class=\"toggle\"><details open=\"\"><summary>Guides</summary><ol><li><a href=\"/en-US/docs/Web/API/Server-sent_events/Using_server-sent_events\">Using server-sent events</a></li></ol></details></li><li class=\"toggle\"><details open=\"\"><summary>Interfaces</summary><ol><li><a href=\"/en-US/docs/Web/API/EventSource\"><code>EventSource</code></a></li></ol></details></li></ol>","body":[{"type":"prose","value":{"id":null,"title":null,"isH3":false,"content":"<p>Traditionally, a web page has to send a request to the server to receive new data; that is, the page requests data from the server. With server-sent events, it's possible for a server to send new data to a web page at any time, by pushing messages to the web page. These incoming messages can be treated as <em><a href=\"/en-US/docs/Web/API/Event\">Events</a> + data</em> inside the web page.</p><div class=\"notecard note\" id=\"sect1\">\n  <p><strong>Note:</strong> This feature is available in <a href=\"/en-US/docs/Web/API/Web_Workers_API\">Web Workers</a></p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"notecard note\" id=\"sect2\">\n  <p><strong>Note:</strong> Firefox does not currently support the use of server-sent events in service workers (it does support them in dedicated and shared workers). See <a href=\"https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/show_bug.cgi?id=1681218\" class=\"external\" rel=\" noopener\">bug&nbsp;1681218</a>.</p>\n</div>"}},{"type":"prose","value":{"id":"concepts_and_usage","title":"Concepts and usage","isH3":false,"content":"<p>To learn how to use server-sent events, see our article <a href=\"/en-US/docs/Web/API/Server-sent_events/Using_server-sent_events\">Using server-sent events</a>.</p>"}},{"type":"prose","value":{"id":"interfaces","title":"Interfaces","isH3":false,"content":"<dl>\n  <dt id=\"eventsource\"><a href=\"/en-US/docs/Web/API/EventSource\"><code>EventSource</code></a></dt>\n  <dd>\n    <p>Defines all the features that handle connecting to a server, receiving events/data, errors, closing a connection, etc.</p>\n  </dd>\n</dl>"}},{"type":"prose","value":{"id":"examples","title":"Examples","isH3":false,"content":"<ul>\n  <li><a href=\"https://github.com/mdn/dom-examples/tree/main/server-sent-events\" class=\"external\" rel=\" noopener\">Simple SSE demo using PHP</a></li>\n</ul>"}},{"type":"specifications","value":{"title":"Specifications","id":"specifications","isH3":false,"specifications":[{"bcdSpecificationURL":"https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/server-sent-events.html#server-sent-events","title":"HTML Standard"}],"query":"undefined"}},{"type":"prose","value":{"id":"see_also","title":"See also","isH3":false,"content":""}},{"type":"prose","value":{"id":"tools","title":"Tools","isH3":true,"content":"<ul>\n  <li><a href=\"https://mercure.rocks\" class=\"external\" rel=\" noopener\">Mercure: a real-time communication protocol (publish-subscribe) built on top of SSE</a></li>\n  <li><a href=\"https://github.com/EventSource/eventsource\" class=\"external\" rel=\" noopener\">EventSource polyfill for Node.js</a></li>\n  <li>Remy Sharp's <a href=\"https://github.com/remy/polyfills/blob/master/EventSource.js\" class=\"external\" rel=\" noopener\">EventSource polyfill</a></li>\n  <li>Yaffle's <a href=\"https://github.com/Yaffle/EventSource\" class=\"external\" rel=\" noopener\">EventSource polyfill</a></li>\n  <li>Rick Waldron's <a href=\"https://github.com/rwaldron/jquery.eventsource\" class=\"external\" rel=\" noopener\">jquery plugin</a></li>\n  <li>intercooler.js <a href=\"https://intercoolerjs.org/docs.html#sse\" class=\"external\" rel=\" noopener\">declarative SSE support</a></li>\n</ul>"}},{"type":"prose","value":{"id":"related_topics","title":"Related Topics","isH3":true,"content":"<ul>\n  <li><a href=\"/en-US/docs/Web/Guide/AJAX\">AJAX</a></li>\n  <li><a href=\"/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript\">JavaScript</a></li>\n  <li><a href=\"/en-US/docs/Web/API/WebSockets_API\">WebSockets</a></li>\n</ul>"}},{"type":"prose","value":{"id":"other_resources","title":"Other resources","isH3":true,"content":"<ul>\n  <li>A <a href=\"https://hacks.mozilla.org/2011/06/a-wall-powered-by-eventsource-and-server-sent-events/\" class=\"external\" rel=\" noopener\">Twitter like application</a> powered by server-sent events and <a href=\"https://github.com/mozilla/webowonder-demos/tree/master/demos/friends%20timeline\" class=\"external\" rel=\" noopener\">its code on GitHub</a>.</li>\n  <li><a href=\"https://dsheiko.com/weblog/html5-and-server-sent-events/\" class=\"external\" rel=\" noopener\">HTML5 and Server-sent events</a></li>\n</ul>"}}],"toc":[{"text":"Concepts and usage","id":"concepts_and_usage"},{"text":"Interfaces","id":"interfaces"},{"text":"Examples","id":"examples"},{"text":"Specifications","id":"specifications"},{"text":"See also","id":"see_also"}],"summary":"Traditionally, a web page has to send a request to the server to receive new data; that is, the page requests data from the server. With server-sent events, it's possible for a server to send new data to a web page at any time, by pushing messages to the web page. These incoming messages can be treated as Events + data inside the web page.","popularity":0.0053,"modified":"2022-09-09T05:18:40.000Z","other_translations":[{"title":"Server-sent events","locale":"es","native":"Español"},{"title":"Server-sent events","locale":"fr","native":"Français"},{"title":"サーバー送信イベント","locale":"ja","native":"日本語"},{"title":"Server-sent events","locale":"ko","native":"한국어"},{"title":"Server-sent events","locale":"pt-BR","native":"Português (do Brasil)"},{"title":"Server-sent events","locale":"ru","native":"Русский"},{"title":"Server-sent events","locale":"zh-CN","native":"中文 (简体)"},{"title":"Server